observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Treasurer to:

 Submit all missing disbursement vouchers to the accounting office for proper recording in the books of the LGU;

Prepare the RCI containing all checks issued during the period and submit this to the Accounting Office together with corresponding DVs;

Ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the DVs before the paid transactions are transmitted to the accounting office; and

Observe the 90 day period within which to submit the missing DVs before suspensions mature into disallowance.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant prepare and record JEV upon receipt of DVs and supporting documents to adjust and correct balances of the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management require the MAO and GSO to:
compare and reconcile their records and to correct/adjust whatever discrepancies;
include/account the properties recorded in the GL/SL but not included in the physical count as of December 31, 2021;
record in the book of accounts those properties found in the official station/office which are not recorded in the GL/SL, but included in the physical count and still owned by the agency;
maintain subsidiary ledgers/PPELC and property cards for each PPE account; and
conduct reconciliation of their records regularly/periodically to immediately notice and adjust if there are discrepancies/unreconciled items, in compliance with Section 53(b) of GAAM, Volume III.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to require the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the required DV and JEV for the fund transfer from the Trust Fund to the General Fund amounting to ₱5,000,000.00 together with all supporting documents;
Return back to the General Fund from the Trust Fund the amount of ₱543,156.63 by effecting correct and proper journal entries based from previously recorded journal entries;
Dispense accounting functions responsibly in adherence with its mandate to review supporting documents before preparation of vouchers to determine completeness of requirements; and
Strictly comply with Section 474 (b) (5) of RA No. 7160 and Sections 4(1), 84(1) and 111(2) of PD No. 1445

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive requires the:
Municipal Accountant to record receivables from the Municipal Treasurer amounting to ₱2,400.00;
Municipal Treasurer to:
pay the LGU the amount of ₱2,400.00 as replenishment for the deduction made against its deposits with the bank;
devise/customize own monitoring strategy to keep control of the cash deposits with the bank; and
strictly comply with Section 2 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that the Management instruct the AMT to:
record the collections in the cash book upon remittances of the Collecting Officers;
reconcile the running balance in the cashbook with the cash on hand at the end of the day/month in compliance with Paragraph D under Section 63 of LTO Manual;
require the Collecting Officers to maintain their own cash book to record all their collections during the day and its subsequent remittance to the Municipal Treasurer; and
require the COs to remit the collections to the AMT daily/regularly.

We recommended that Management:
instruct the GSO to notify the office of the Auditor within twenty-four (24) hours from acceptance, the time, date and place of delivery to give the AT ample time in the conduct of inspection;
instruct the GSO Designate and the Inspection Officer to properly fill-out the AIR and submit the same within the prescribed period, and;
to submit scanned copy of notification of delivery including the supporting documents to AT via e-mail considering the risks of COVID-19 and travel time from the LGU to Provincial Satellite Auditing Office (PSAO) and vice-versa.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

the MSWD Officer to conduct proper verification and validation of the targeted beneficiaries;

grant ESP and other similar benefits only to duly qualified recipients observing the prohibitions stated in DSWD MC No. 09, Series of 2020;

cause the immediate refund of the amount paid to the beneficiaries who are not qualified to receive the grant by informing them through writing;

redistribute the refunded amounts to identified eligible beneficiaries, if warranted or return the amount to the Bureau of Treasury;

the MSWD to introduce more control procedures such as but not limited to:
Assign staff only to consolidate and deduplicate all target beneficiaries in Pandan before transmitting them to the DSWD FO.  Should this be improbable due to scarce time and limited manpower, the LGU may opt to detect duplication prior to liquidation and then immediately cause redistribution; 
Instruct barangay officials to provide copies of written instructions on filling out the SAC forms with complete and accurate information to prevent duplication of entry in the master list when ran for deduplication.  Should the beneficiary is unable to write; the barangay council shall provide assistance;
Create simplified and summarized guidelines issued by the DSWD to be given to all PBs and urge them to reproduce more copies for their information campaign within their jurisdiction; and
Devise a tool or questionnaire-type device that will aid the barangay officials in identifying target beneficiaries.

the Office of the Mayor and MSWD to:
Urge all PBs to maintain close coordination and communication with their constituents to deter people from taking advantage of the weakness in the system;
Encourage potential recipients to uphold guidelines to mitigate issues and avoid administrative cases that may be filed against them;
Request the cooperation and utmost support of all barangay officials to achieve a high success rate in implementing various programs of the LGU and the National Government; and
Provide the SAC forms only to the vulnerable sectors and to the poor families.

Encouraged various LGU offices to update the Listahanan database that will contain necessary information of families in the municipality of Pandan and to mitigate the deliberate misrepresentation of any person.   The National and Local Government will use this system for implementation of future projects and derive benefits therefrom in various ways such as but not limited to:

List of all families requiring relief goods in times of crisis and state of calamity. The LGU can readily quantify the number of goods needed to be procured and speed up the distribution process;

Facilitate identification of targeted beneficiaries who require specific support from the government and maintain records of families who already received or constantly receiving assistance; and

Eliminate chances of double payment of assistance.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

the PESO Manager/Local TUPAD Coordinator to:

review and verify the validity of documents submitted by target beneficiaries;

provide written SAP guidelines particularly on grant of TUPAD cash assistance and prohibitions stated in Item 7.5.1 of DSWD-DOLE-DTI-DA-DOF-DBM-DILG JMC Circular No. 1 and DOLE Administrative Order No. 114 series of 2020 for reference of barangay officials and other interested parties;
perform adequate profiling and validation of prospective beneficiaries to detect duplications before submitting the list of beneficiaries to the oversight agency for approval; 

Encourage barangay officials to cooperate in fair and proper implementation of national and local programs; and

AMT and MA, as assisted by the Local TUPAD Coordinator, to demand the immediate refund of the amount paid to ineligible beneficiaries.  Amounts refunded shall be returned to DOLE as stated in the MOA

